Apteris wrote:I'm getting so very frustrated with this bullshit.Words, words, words, nothing happens. Words, words, travel words, nothing happens. Travel words, a brief description of something actually interesting that is too short, after which again nothing happens.I'm 40% of the way through ADWD and I don't know why I still bother. I've found much that resonates with me in MotherJones' review of the book:Nick Baumann of Mother Jones wrote:A writer who has become obsessed with travel timelines and minor details will produce a book that seems, well, obsessed with travel timelines and minor details. [..]The problem is that most of that travelling and scene-setting is boring [..]And by the end of A Dance With Dragons, neither Victarion Greyjoy nor Tyrion Lannister has even met Daenerys Targaryen in person. They've basically spent the entire book traveling.This is just outrageous. Already I'm bored with Tyrion's interminable journey and Daenerys' interminable dawdling. Now I learn that all those people who were supposed to reach Daenerys, don't. Neither will the Others--from what I've heard--assault the Wall before the end of the book. Seriously, what's left that's interesting? I can't wait to see how many thousands of pages Spoiler: show
Davos' quest for Rickon
will take.GRRM has indicated that he could, if he felt like it, write some good fantasy, as opposed to only good palace intrigues. I want to learn more about Valyria. I want to learn more about the Others. I want to know more about the gods in the books. I want to know what that book in Oldtown is all about. You know, the one that was alluded to around 20% of the way through book 5, in relation to the key that was stolen 1300 pages before in the prologue to AFfC? Yeah. I wouldn't mind some more fantasy and some less absurdly convoluted references.I swear, I'm very tempted to just read a synopsis of what happens and throw the book on the fire.Anyway, two more quotes to finish this post.David Orr of the New York Times wrote:This series is long. “A Dance With Dragons” comes in at roughly 9,574,622,012 pages, and smart money says the final two books in the series will make this one look like “The Old Man and the Sea.” Such length isn’t necessary, and it hurts Martin’s prose and his plot mechanics.Nick Baumann of Mother Jones wrote:Thankfully, there's a solution readily available. It's called editing.Haha, as if.Unfortunately, if all a reader thinks that has happened during that time is "they were traveling" then the reader is very likely skimming the book and/or not paying attention anyway.
Apteris
